gan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Christology- Neccesary ressurection.</span><hr size=1> For Reference:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>From that time Jesus began to show his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many things from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and on the third day be raised. MAT 16:21 RSV<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, right off the start, there is no mention of &quot;how&quot; Jesus was to be raised.  That was clarified later in the Gospel when He appeared to the disciples.<br>
<br>
So, would there be an effect upon Christianity if Jesus rose spiritually an not physically.  Again, a number of points to consider.<br>
<br>
1)  As long as He was raised from the dead you could say that the victory over death has been accomplished.  Some would argue that the method is not important.  However, I could counter that by saying that with Christ, a physical resurrection makes the victory over death &quot;complete&quot;.<br>
<br>
2)  Christ, being bodily resurrected and then His assumption into heaven creates an interesting theological consideration.  Christ is God yet considering His bodily resurrection still (theoretically) retains some measure of His human nature.  While that isn't necessarily important, I think that connects God and humanity in a very special and unique way.  Now, I'll avoid saying whether that was the case &quot;before&quot; the resurrection when you consider God's atemporal (totally outside of time as we know it) nature.  Reason for avoiding making a pronouncement on that - I just don't know what the answer would be.<br>
<br>
3)  In all honesty, spreading the Gospel message would have been more difficult with only a spiritual resurrection.  If Christ had not risen bodily on the third day, His body would still be lying in the tomb provided by Joseph of Arimathea.  The angels would not have had to come to push away the stone, the guards would not have fleed after witnessing the event.  Additionally, the disciples could have gone around saying &quot;He is alive&quot; all they wanted, but the enemies of Jesus would have simply gone to the tomb, pointed at the body and said, &quot;nope, still dead.&quot;<br>
<br>
On that final point alone, I think the bodily resurrection is extremely important even though not absolutely theologically necessary.  While some would have still belived and come to be Christians, I think that would have been a harder evangelical sell if the body of Jesus remained in the tomb.  It is human nature to be skeptical and the body of Christ remaining in the tomb would be just one more point available to instill doubt into potential followers.<br>
<br>
It is an interesting question you have posed.  While I can't definitively say that the bodily resurrection is necessary, I think it is vitally important and makes Christianity that much more tangible for those who follow Christ.<br>
<br>
 <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
