ol too emphasize the importance of the bodily resurrection.  I tried too answer this question from two different angels historical-sociological. The main points being:<br>
1. No resurrection (NR) would mean that the biggest evidence for Jesus being the son of God would not be valid.<br>
2. NR would historically probably reduce the growth of the early Christian sect so they wouldn't be able too grow as fast as they did ( Esdras was on to this).<br>
3. NR in flesh would not be in accordance with Messiah prophecy.<br>
4. NR would also give gnosticism right- since they believe that Jesus was mostly spirit an the flesh part of him just a vessel.<br>
<br>
Systematically it would seriously impair &quot;Jesus as victor over death&quot; theory which was essential for mission in the early days and is still important in today as such. <br>
Today however Jesus as sacrificial lamb too atone for our sins is more important too most people. The interesting thing is that NR wouldn't in theory destroy this aspect. But in real life it probably would. This because of the historical repercussions.<br>
I am actively using all your answers in my studies so I thank you all.  The paper I turned in on this is in Norwegian so you cant have it I'm sorry. I especially like too cross reference your answers with your denominations. (Jeff on this one you are alike your European brothers.Houmenna!)       <br>
